1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,087
To understand the relation between these two worlds,

2
00:00:03,187 --> 00:00:06,151
let's first consider the simple world of classical

3
00:00:06,251 --> 00:00:09,277
propositional logic, also known as 0th order logic.

4
00:00:09,333 --> 00:00:12,252
Here we have a set of propositional variables,

5
00:00:12,352 --> 00:00:14,483
which can either be true or false.

6
00:00:15,066 --> 00:00:18,024
These serve as the atoms of our logic, which

7
00:00:18,124 --> 00:00:22,195
we can combine using the Boolean connectives of conjunction,

8
00:00:22,295 --> 00:00:26,852
disjunction, implication and negation to form proposition formulas.

9
00:00:26,933 --> 00:00:30,635
The connectives are governed by truth tables, where conjunction,

10
00:00:30,735 --> 00:00:33,546
disjunction, and negation are as we would expect.

11
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:40,153
In classical logic, implication is equivalent to 'not p or q', meaning that p

12
00:00:40,253 --> 00:00:44,732
implies q is true either if p is false, or q is true.

13
00:00:44,800 --> 00:00:49,417
Note that there are non-classical logics which interpret these symbols differently,

14
00:00:49,517 --> 00:00:53,281
especially implication and negation. We will cover this in the bonus

15
00:00:53,381 --> 00:00:56,350
video at the end, for now we stick to classical logic.

16
00:00:57,400 --> 00:01:01,883
So, given an arbitrary propositional formula, like this one,

17
00:01:01,983 --> 00:01:05,397
we can easily evaluate it using a truth table.

18
00:01:05,466 --> 00:01:08,573
Meaning that we list every possible combination of 0 and

19
00:01:08,673 --> 00:01:12,123
1 for the propositional variables involved in the formula, and

20
00:01:12,223 --> 00:01:15,502
then compute the output using the rules of the connectives.

21
00:01:15,600 --> 00:01:18,993
If all rows evaluate to 1, as is the case with

22
00:01:19,093 --> 00:01:23,702
this formula, then we say that the formula is logically valid.

23
00:01:23,800 --> 00:01:25,971
If all rows evaluate to 0, then

24
00:01:26,071 --> 00:01:28,976
we say that the formula is unsatisfiable.

25
00:01:29,133 --> 00:01:34,701
And if at least one row is true, then we say that it is satisfiable.

26
00:01:34,866 --> 00:01:37,749
We see that each row in the truth table represents

27
00:01:37,849 --> 00:01:41,866
a specific interpretation of the propositional variables. So each row

28
00:01:41,966 --> 00:01:44,849
can be seen as a possible world or interpretation.

